ary texts, film, television, music, visual art, and games. It will prove an invaluable source of reference for students of literary and visual arts, general readers, collectors, librarians, and cultural historians--indeed, by anyone interested in the history of the waysin which Camelot has figured in post-medieval English-speaking cultures.ANN F. HOWEY is Assistant Professor at Brock University, Canada; STEPHEN R. REIMER is Associate Professor at the University of Alberta, Canada  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aArthurian romancesvBibliography. 0aEnglish literaturevBibliography. 4aBibliography & Manuscripts. 4aEnglish & American Literature. 4aFilm & Theatre. 4aMedieval Literature. 7aREFERENCE / Bibliographies & Indexes.2bisacsh  aArt.  aArthurian Legend.  aCamelot.  aEnglish-Speaking Cultures.  aFilm-Makers.  aLiterary Texts.  aModern Fiction.  aMusic.  aMusicians.  aPainters.  aTelevision.  aTennyson.  aVictorian Era.1 aReimer, Stephen R., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package pre 2013z978311143139040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978184615449240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781846154492423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781846154492/original  a978-3-11-143139-0  Boydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package pre 2013b2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles